{{multiple image| align = left | direction = horizontal | header = | header_align = left/right/center | footer = '''Left image''': [[Minerva]] on a [[Roman Republic|Roman]] [[gilding|gilt]]-silver plate, 1st century BCE; a similar Roman gilt-silver plate found in [[Jingyuan County, Gansu]] province, China, dated 2nd or 3rd century CE had a raised relief image of the [[Greco-Roman]] god [[Dionysos]].<ref>Harper (2002), 106 (Fig. 6).</ref><br> '''Right image''': A Western-Han blue-glass bowl; although the Chinese had been making glass bead items since the [[Spring and Autumn Period]] (722<U+2013>481 BCE), the first Chinese glasswares (such as bowls and bottles) appeared during Western Han.<ref name="an 2002 79 83"/>| footer_align = left | image1 = Athena-Schale Hildesheimer Silberfund.jpg | width1 = 140 | image2 = Western Han blue glass bowl.JPG | width2 = 160}}

The establishment of the [[Silk Road]] occurred during Wu's reign, owing to the efforts of the diplomat [[Zhang Qian]]. The increased demand for silk from the [[Roman Empire]] stimulated commercial traffic in both Central Asia and across the [[Indian Ocean]]. [[Roman commerce|Roman merchants]] sailed to [[Barbarikon]] near present-day [[Karachi]], [[Pakistan]], and [[Bharuch|Barygaza]] in present-day [[Gujarat]], [[India]] to purchase Chinese silks (see [[Roman trade with India]]).<ref name="liu 1988 19">Liu (1988), 19.</ref> When Emperor Wu conquered [[Nanyue]]<U+2014>in what is now [[Southwest China]] and [[Northern and southern Vietnam|northern Vietnam]]<U+2014>in 111 BCE, overseas trade was extended to [[Southeast Asia]] and the Indian Ocean, as maritime merchants traded Han gold and silk for pearls, jade, lapis lazuli, and glasswares.<ref name="nishijima 1986 579 580">Nishijima (1986), 579<U+2013>580.</ref> 

The [[Book of Later Han]] states that Roman envoys sent by Emperor [[Marcus Aurelius]] (r. 161<U+2013>180 CE), following a southern route, brought gifts to the court of [[Emperor Huan of Han]] (r. 146<U+2013>168 CE) in 166 CE.<ref>Liu (1988), 19; de Crespigny (2007), 600; Nishijima (1986), 579<U+2013>580"</ref> This Roman mission followed an unsuccessful attempt by the Han diplomat [[Gan Ying]] to reach [[Rome]] in 97. Gan Ying was delayed in [[Anxi (Parthia)|Anxi]], near the [[Persian Gulf]], by Arsacid [[Parthia]]n authorities, and could only make a report on Rome based on oral accounts.<ref name="nishijima 1986 579">Nishijima (1986), 579.</ref><ref>de Crespigny (2007), 239<U+2013>240.</ref><ref>Y<U+00FC> (1986), 460<U+2013>461.</ref> Historians [[Charles Hucker]] and [[Rafe de Crespigny]] both speculate that the Roman mission of 166 CE involved enterprising Roman merchants instead of actual diplomats;<ref>Hucker (1975), 191; de Crespigny (2007), 600.</ref> Hucker writes:<ref name="hucker 1975 191"/>

<blockquote>Tributary missions from vassal states were commonly allowed to include traders, who thus gained opportunities to do business in the capital markets. No doubt a large proportion of what the Chinese court chose to call tributary missions were in fact shrewdly organized commercial ventures by foreign merchants with no diplomatic status at all. This was unquestionably the case, most notably, with a group of traders who appeared on the south coast in 166 A.D. claiming to be envoys from the Roman emperor Marcus Aurelius Antoninus.<ref name="hucker 1975 191">Hucker (1975), 191.</ref></blockquote>

The main trade route leading into Han China passed first through [[Kashgar]], yet [[Hellenistic civilization|Hellenized]] [[Bactria]] further west was the central node of international trade.<ref name="liu 1988 26">Liu (1988), 26.</ref> By the 1st century CE, Bactria and much of Central Asia and [[North India]] were controlled by the [[Kushan Empire]].<ref>Liu (1988), 26<U+2013>29.</ref> Silk was the main export item from China to [[India]]. [[Economic history of India|Indian merchants]] brought various goods to China, including tortoise shell, gold, silver, copper, iron, lead, tin, fine cloth, woolen textiles, perfume and incense, crystal sugar, pepper, ginger, salt, coral, pearls, glass items, and Roman wares.<ref>Liu (1988), 52<U+2013>53, 64<U+2013>65.</ref> Indian merchants brought Roman [[styrax]] and [[frankincense]] to China, while the Chinese knew [[bdellium]] as a fragrant item from Persia, although it was native to [[West India]].<ref name="liu 1988 63">Liu (1988), 63.</ref> The tall [[Ferghana horse]]s imported from [[Fergana]] were highly prized in Han China.<ref name="liu 1988 53">Liu (1988), 53.</ref> The newly introduced exotic Central Asian [[grape]]s (i.e. ''[[vitis vinifera]]'') were used to make [[Wine in China|grape wine]], although the Chinese had [[rice wine]] before this.<ref name="gernet 1962 134 135">Gernet (1962), 134<U+2013>135.</ref><ref>Temple (1986), 101.</ref> [[Glass]] luxury items from ancient [[Mesopotamia]] have been found in Chinese tombs and dated to the late [[Spring and Autumn Period]] (771<U+2013>476 BCE). [[Roman glass]]wares have been found in Chinese tombs dating to the early 1st century BCE, with the earliest specimen found at the southern Chinese seaport of [[Guangzhou]].<ref name="an 2002 79 83">An (2002), 79, 82<U+2013>83.</ref> [[Silver (household)|Silverwares]] from the Roman Empire and the [[Persian Empire]] of Parthia have also been found in Han Chinese tomb sites.<ref>Harper (2002), 96<U+2013>107.</ref>

